{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17590565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17590565"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0.46,0.14,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66590"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52043"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66590"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOn a global basis carcinoma of the oesophagus is the 11th most common cancers in the world, with more that half a million new cases being reported in 2022. These cancers will either be a squamous cell or adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenocarcinoma accounts for more than 90% of cases","Five-year survival rates are similar between squamous cell and adenocarcinoma","Overall survival rates have improved significantly since the 1970s","Adenocarcinoma is more common in the upper third of the oesophagus","Squamous cell carcinoma is more common in Western countries"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of oesophageal cancer, including progressive dysphagia, weight loss, and risk factors including smoking, alcohol consumption, and Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. Understanding the epidemiology and prognosis of oesophageal cancer types is crucial for clinical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn a global basis, \u003Cstrong\u003Es\u003C/strong\u003Equamous cell carcinoma accounts for more than 90% of cases. Up until the 1970\u0027s this was the situation in Australia and other western communities. However over the last three decades the incidence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eadenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E has increased and these cases now form the majority. These two types comprise over 95% of all oesophageal cancers, with other types such as small cell carcinoma, sarcoma, and lymphoma being rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-year survival rates are similar between squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. While there are differences in risk factors and anatomical distribution, overall survival rates are comparable between the two main types when matched for stage at diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverall survival rates have improved significantly since the 1970s\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Despite advances in surgical techniques, chemotherapy, and radiotherapy, the overall 5-year survival rate remains poor at 15-20%, with only modest improvements over the past several decades.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenocarcinoma is more common in the upper third of the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Adenocarcinoma typically occurs in the lower third of the oesophagus, often arising from Barrett\u0027s oesophagus, while squamous cell carcinoma is more common in the upper and middle thirds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma is more common in Western countries\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In Western countries, adenocarcinoma has become the predominant type, likely due to increasing obesity and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Squamous cell carcinoma remains more common in developing countries and parts of Asia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma account for over 95% of all oesophageal cancers.","Despite advances in treatment, 5-year survival rates for oesophageal cancer remain poor at 15-20%."],"references":["Li J, Xu J, Zheng Y, Gao Y, He S, Li H, Zou K, Li N, Tian J, Chen W, He J. Esophageal cancer: Epidemiology, risk factors and screening. Chin J Cancer Res. 2021 Oct 31;33(5):535-547. doi: 10.21147/j.issn.1000-9604.2021.05.01. PMID: 34815628; PMCID: PMC8580797.","Wang Y, Mukkamalla SKR, Singh R, Babiker HM, Lyons S. Esophageal Cancer. 2024 Aug 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083661.","Codipilly DC, Wang KK. Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Esophagus. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2022 Sep;51(3):457-484. doi: 10.1016/j.gtc.2022.06.005. Epub 2022 Aug 29. PMID: 36153105."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52043"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52043"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T10:12:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T10:13:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7894"}},"con